## What the output confirms

**1. The Kiali CR does *not* manage this binding.** Both `cluster_wide_access` and `accessible_namespaces` came back **empty** — the operator's CR has neither field set, so the `kiali-monitoring` operator is not reconciling a `cluster-monitoring-view` binding by that name. The bindings the operator *does* own are the separate `kiali-monitoring-rbac` / `kiali-monitoring-rbac-1` entries (that's the operator's own namespace-scoped RBAC), **not** `dev-kiali-cluster-monitoring-view`.

**2. Every binding has `ownerRefs=[]`.** Nothing in the cluster has an `ownerReference` to `dev-kiali-cluster-monitoring-view`. Combined with the `last-applied-configuration` annotation you saw earlier, this proves it was created by a **manual `oc apply`** during bootstrap — it is a genuine orphan, not operator-reconciled.

**3. It won't be recreated on delete.** Since no operator and no ownerRef points at it, deleting it will not trigger any controller to bring it back. The only thing that will recreate it is your Helm pipeline — which is exactly what you want.

**Verdict: yes, you can safely delete (or patch) `dev-kiali-cluster-monitoring-view` and let Helm own it.** The operator will not fight you.

## Which to choose — patch vs delete

Both reach the identical end state. My recommendation, in your PCI-DSS environment, is **patch (adopt-in-place)** — it never removes a live RBAC grant, so there's zero permission gap and nothing for a SOC/audit to flag as a dropped-then-recreated cluster binding.

**Patch (recommended):**
```bash
oc annotate clusterrolebinding dev-kiali-cluster-monitoring-view \
  meta.helm.sh/release-name=epay-common \
  meta.helm.sh/release-namespace=dev-epay-common --overwrite

oc label clusterrolebinding dev-kiali-cluster-monitoring-view \
  app.kubernetes.io/managed-by=Helm --overwrite

# verify the stamp took
oc get clusterrolebinding dev-kiali-cluster-monitoring-view \
  -o jsonpath='managed-by={.metadata.labels.app\.kubernetes\.io/managed-by}{" | release="}{.metadata.annotations.meta\.helm\.sh/release-name}{" | ns="}{.metadata.annotations.meta\.helm\.sh/release-namespace}{"\n"}'
```
Expected: `managed-by=Helm | release=epay-common | ns=dev-epay-common`

Then run the deploy pipeline. Helm sees a resource it already owns, upgrade proceeds, no conflict.

**Delete (only if you specifically want a clean recreate):**
```bash
oc delete clusterrolebinding dev-kiali-cluster-monitoring-view
oc get clusterrolebinding dev-kiali-cluster-monitoring-view -w   # confirm it stays absent ~15s, Ctrl-C
# run pipeline, then verify ownership as above
```
Brief impact: Kiali's monitoring/graph panels lose Prometheus data for the seconds between delete and pipeline recreate. No payment service affected.

## One important thing before you run the pipeline

Your grep earlier showed the error stops at the **first** conflicting object, but this same orphan-adoption problem almost certainly affects the sibling bindings too. The chart renders three Kiali CRBs plus two Tempo CRBs, all cluster-scoped. Check them **now** so the pipeline doesn't just fail again on the next one:

```bash
for crb in dev-kiali-cluster-monitoring-view dev-kiali-dev-istio-system-oauth dev-kiali; do
  echo "== $crb =="
  oc get clusterrolebinding "$crb" \
    -o jsonpath='exists=yes managed-by={.metadata.labels.app\.kubernetes\.io/managed-by}{" release="}{.metadata.annotations.meta\.helm\.sh/release-name}{"\n"}' 2>/dev/null \
    || echo "absent (Helm will create fresh — no conflict)"
done
# Tempo cluster-scoped bindings from the same chart:
oc get clusterrolebinding | grep -Ei 'tempo' 
```

For any that come back **existing but without `managed-by=Helm`**, apply the same patch (adjust `meta.helm.sh/release-namespace` if that object's release namespace differs). Any that come back **absent** are fine — Helm creates them cleanly.

Also note `uat-kiali-cluster-monitoring-view` in your list — when you replicate this to UAT you'll hit the identical issue there, so plan the same patch for that release.

## Fix the chart so this never recurs

Two changes to make in the repo so fresh clusters and future upgrades stay clean:

The `monitoring` CRB template (`templates/kiali/kiali-clusterrolebinding.yaml`) renders no labels/annotations, unlike its viewer/oauth siblings. Align it:
```yaml
metadata:
  name: {{ .Values.monitoring.kiali.rbac.clusterRoleBindings.monitoring.name }}
  labels:
    {{- toYaml .Values.monitoring.kiali.rbac.labels | nindent 4 }}
  annotations:
    {{- toYaml .Values.monitoring.kiali.rbac.annotations | nindent 4 }}
```
Caveat: those values include `operator-sdk/primary-resource` annotations copied from the operator. They're cosmetic here (the operator doesn't own this object, per your output), but if you'd rather not imply operator ownership on a Helm-managed object, drop those two annotation lines from the `rbac.annotations` block for this binding.

## Rollback plan

Your full backup is already at `/tmp/crb-live-full.yaml`. Stage a clean re-appliable copy first:
```bash
oc get clusterrolebinding dev-kiali-cluster-monitoring-view -o yaml \
  | grep -vE '^\s*(uid|resourceVersion|creationTimestamp|generation):' \
  > /tmp/crb-rollback.yaml
```

- **If you patched and want to revert to the orphan state:**
  ```bash
  oc annotate clusterrolebinding dev-kiali-cluster-monitoring-view \
    meta.helm.sh/release-name- meta.helm.sh/release-namespace-
  oc label clusterrolebinding dev-kiali-cluster-monitoring-view app.kubernetes.io/managed-by-
  ```
- **If you deleted and need it back immediately:**
  ```bash
  oc apply -f /tmp/crb-rollback.yaml
  ```
- **If the Helm upgrade partially applied then failed:**
  ```bash
  helm history epay-common -n dev-epay-common
  helm rollback epay-common <LAST_GOOD_REVISION> -n dev-epay-common
  ```

Post-rollback sanity check that Kiali can still read monitoring:
```bash
oc auth can-i get pods \
  --as=system:serviceaccount:dev-istio-system:dev-kiali-service-account \
  -n openshift-monitoring
# expect: yes
```

Bottom line: the operator is not in play, the binding is a manual orphan, semantics match the chart exactly — **patch it** (cleanest), sweep the sibling CRBs for the same condition, then run the pipeline. Harden the template so UAT and prod replication don't repeat this.
